  "prompt": "What does it mean when you have blood clots but no period?",
  "response": "Having blood clots without a period can be concerning and may indicate several potential underlying issues. Here are some possible causes:\n\n1. **Early Pregnancy Complications**: Blood clots without a period could be a sign of a miscarriage or ectopic pregnancy, particularly if accompanied by abdominal pain, cramping, or other symptoms.\n\n2. **Hormonal Imbalance**: Irregular hormonal fluctuations can cause abnormal uterine bleeding, sometimes leading to the passing of blood clots even without a regular period.\n\n3. **Uterine Polyps or Fibroids**: These non-cancerous growths in the uterus can cause irregular bleeding and the formation of blood clots.\n\n4. **Pelvic Inflammatory Disease (PID)**: An infection of the reproductive organs can lead to unusual bleeding and clotting.\n\n5. **Thickened Uterine Lining (Endometrial Hyperplasia)**: An abnormally thickened uterine lining can result in irregular bleeding and clots.\n\n6. **Birth Control Side Effects**: Hormonal contraceptives or intrauterine devices (IUDs) can sometimes cause irregular bleeding or clotting.\n\n7. **Trauma or Injury**: Physical trauma to the pelvic area or vaginal canal can lead to bleeding and clotting.\n\n8. **Clotting Disorders**: Conditions that affect blood clotting, such as von Willebrand disease or other bleeding disorders, can cause abnormal bleeding and clots.\n\n9. **Menopause or Perimenopause**: Hormonal changes during this transition can cause irregular bleeding and clotting.\n\n10. **Cancer**: In rare cases, uterine or cervical cancer may cause abnormal bleeding and clotting.\n\nIf you experience blood clots without a period, it\u2019s important to consult a healthcare provider for an evaluation. They may perform a physical exam, blood tests, ultrasound, or other diagnostic tests to determine the cause and provide appropriate treatment.",
